      "site_admin": false
    },
    "created_at": "2017-04-22T01:32:23Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-04-22T01:36:40Z",
    "body": "What do you think about just introducing the options for the paths where to store each category of files (user-specific configuration ($XDG_CONFIG_HOME), user-specific data ($XDG_DATA_HOME) and user-specific non-essential data files ($XDG_CACHE_HOME)) with their default values set to the current locations? This way each app based on Electron could implement its own way of handling the issue.\r\n\r\nI'm using 2 e-based apps: Atom editor & Wire messenger. This topic for Atom is already quite discussed in the referenced issue above, the Wire issue is this: https://github.com/wireapp/wire-desktop/issues/521.\r\n\r\nWhat happens with Wire is that the cache stores all transferred files, among other things, and the `.config` folder grows to GBs, frequently exceeding 10Gb. For a home user this is not an issue, but for enterprise environments this is a major issue and a reason for not adopting the app.\r\n\r\nBased on the discussion in the above-mentioned Wire issue, there's no way for Wire to define the paths on its own, the change should be implemented in Electron.\r\n\r\nIf Electron would have variables for each group of files, Wire developers could manage the migration of current data in each folder for their app. At the same time, all other e-apps would be unaffected. And once their developers discover the new options, they could make a decision best suited for their users."
  },
  {
